WEBVTT

00:03.522 --> 00:04.804
Welcome to Gospel in Life.

00:05.485 --> 00:09.330
Why do some people grow through suffering while others are crushed by it?

00:09.350 --> 00:15.238
Peter says the answer begins with holiness, giving our thoughts and our actions fully over to God.

00:15.819 --> 00:26.994
Today Tim Keller shows us how to turn our whole selves over to the God who can transform our character and turn us into people who live joyfully, even in life's most difficult moments.

00:34.082 --> 00:39.669
the last several weeks, and for one more week, we're looking at 1 Peter 1, 13 to 21.

00:42.933 --> 00:43.514
Read with me.

00:46.638 --> 00:50.022
Therefore, prepare your minds for action.

00:50.683 --> 00:51.804
Be self-controlled.

00:52.525 --> 00:56.730
Set your hope fully on the grace to be given you when Jesus Christ is revealed.

00:57.711 --> 01:03.218
As obedient children, do not conform to the evil desires you had when you lived in ignorance.

01:03.906 --> 01:13.616
But just as he who called you is holy, so be holy in all you do, for it is written be holy because I am holy.

01:14.637 --> 01:21.584
Since you call on a father who judges each man's work impartially, live your lives as strangers here in reverent fear.

01:22.264 --> 01:31.794
For you know that it was not with perishable things such as silver or gold that you were redeemed from the empty way of life handed down to you from your forefathers.

01:31.906 --> 01:41.938
But with the precious blood of Christ, a lamb without blemish or defect, he was chosen before the creation of the world that was revealed in these last times for your sake.

01:42.779 --> 01:52.151
Through him, you believe in God, who raised him from the dead, and glorified him, and so your faith and hope are in God.

01:54.073 --> 01:55.034
This is God's word.

01:55.094 --> 02:01.362
Now, what we're looking at, and what we have been looking at, is the subject of holiness

02:02.114 --> 02:02.715
holiness.

02:03.496 --> 02:23.701
And we said that the passage that Peter quotes from out of the Old Testament, out of the book of Leviticus, be holy for I am holy, takes the main Hebrew word for holy in the Bible, holiness, the word kadosh, which means to cut it off, to separate.

02:25.082 --> 02:31.410
And we said when holiness refers to God, what it means is he's off our scales, he's transcendently above us.

02:31.810 --> 02:33.693
He's not like anything we can imagine.

02:34.594 --> 02:40.462
And we also said, however, when you apply the word holy to us, what is a holy person?

02:41.824 --> 02:43.987
What it means is we are set apart.

02:45.028 --> 02:47.011
We're separated unto God.

02:47.272 --> 02:50.376
Now that's a religious sounding word.

02:50.676 --> 02:51.838
You sang about it tonight.

02:52.299 --> 02:54.201
Did you notice that in your first song?

02:55.363 --> 02:56.965
You have called us out of darkness.

02:57.025 --> 03:00.530
You say, we are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, buy your grace.

03:00.674 --> 03:04.461
we are a holy nation, and therefore we're set apart.

03:05.242 --> 03:18.226
And we said last week, if you want to get a real trite illustration of what it means to be holy, just imagine yourself reading a newspaper, you're reading it, getting information, and yet

03:18.434 --> 03:23.582
As you're reading through it, suddenly there is one article with some information that you can use.

03:23.642 --> 03:25.164
You want to use it in a sales pitch.

03:25.184 --> 03:26.306
You want to use it in a paper.

03:26.346 --> 03:28.009
You want to use it in a promotion.

03:28.249 --> 03:28.850
You want to use it.

03:28.910 --> 03:31.114
The only way to use it is to set it apart.

03:31.935 --> 03:33.257
You've got to cut it out of the paper.

03:33.758 --> 03:36.261
You've got to set it apart from the newspaper.

03:37.043 --> 03:37.363
Why?

03:37.383 --> 03:39.106
If you don't do that, you can't use it.

03:40.708 --> 03:47.058
And so to cut something out, to set it apart for your use is exactly what the Bible means.

03:47.138 --> 03:48.339
when it talks about being holy.

03:48.960 --> 03:51.903
So every week we'll come back to this and look at it from another perspective.

03:52.644 --> 03:57.609
See, to be a holy person is not at all what people popularly think.

03:58.330 --> 04:03.155
I mean, at the worst, the word holy is a terrible word, you know, in modern English now.

04:03.195 --> 04:10.063
When we use the word holy, we almost always mean something, oh, imperious, something inaccessible maybe.

04:10.604 --> 04:16.530
We use the word holy to refer to holier than thou, condescending, self-righteous,

04:16.802 --> 04:21.288
At the very best, people think of a holy person as somebody who keeps all the rules.

04:22.090 --> 04:22.670
Don't you see?

04:22.710 --> 04:26.015
This goes way so much deeper than keeping all the rules.

04:26.956 --> 04:33.426
Holiness is an attitude of heart in which you look at God and you say, use me.

04:35.328 --> 04:37.491
This is a tremendous clash with modern culture.

04:37.512 --> 04:39.154
In modern culture, you're supposed to be independent.

04:39.174 --> 04:40.576
You're not supposed to let anybody use you.

04:41.858 --> 04:44.882
But that's the antithesis to this.

04:45.282 --> 04:51.269
A holy person is someone who looks at God and says, not just give me the rules, tell me what the rules are so I can get to it, no.

04:53.132 --> 04:55.615
A holy person is someone who says, I belong to you.

04:57.056 --> 04:58.338
I am set apart for you.

05:00.200 --> 05:02.603
And that's what we've been trying to get at each week.

05:02.643 --> 05:05.347
Now, last week, we talked about holiness of mind.

05:05.387 --> 05:08.551
To be holy means to be holy his.

05:09.812 --> 05:11.014
To holy belong to him.

05:11.054 --> 05:14.578
And so that means, first of all, we talk about the mind.

05:14.850 --> 05:17.194
Now this week and next week, let's talk about the life.

05:17.295 --> 05:24.628
It's great to say that to be holy means you have to submit your mind to God and submit your beliefs and so forth.

05:25.109 --> 05:36.210
But a person who submits the mind without submitting the life, the heart and the will, is a hypocrite and we hate them.

05:36.994 --> 05:41.839
And therefore, to be a holy doesn't, it means more than just to give him your mind, you have to give him your life.

05:42.280 --> 05:48.546
And what we're going to look at here today is a depiction of what a holy life is.

05:49.547 --> 05:56.354
And it's really right here in these verses, as obedient children do not conform to the evil desires you had when you lived in ignorance.

05:57.435 --> 06:03.922
Since you call on a father who judges each man's work impartially, live your lives as strangers here in reverent fear.

06:04.226 --> 06:15.203
For it was not with perishable things such as silver or gold that you were redeemed from the empty way of life handed down to you from your forefathers, but with the precious blood of Christ, a lamb without blemish or defect.

06:16.685 --> 06:20.371
There's a contrast here between a life without God and a holy life.

06:20.471 --> 06:27.202
And if we look at the contrast, we'll continue to get a better feel for what it means to be holy, for he is holy.

06:27.883 --> 06:29.385
Okay, first, first contrast.

06:30.127 --> 06:32.370
A life without God is ignorant.

06:33.378 --> 06:37.904
But a life of holiness integrates the thought and the life.

06:39.686 --> 06:44.813
Holiness, remember, we said the word holiness comes from the English word holness.

06:46.075 --> 06:48.879
And therefore, there is a bifurcation.

06:48.919 --> 06:52.984
The life without God is a bifurcation of thought and action.

06:53.745 --> 06:58.331
But a holy life means an integration, a coherent integration of thought and life.

06:58.371 --> 06:59.733
Let me explain this.

07:00.654 --> 07:03.378
Most people in Manhattan who don't believe

07:03.938 --> 07:10.970
in God or Christianity, they think they don't believe in it because they know too much, because they think too much.

07:11.030 --> 07:14.535
They say, you know, there's Christians, that's great for some people.

07:14.576 --> 07:15.757
They're religious, fine.

07:16.519 --> 07:19.424
But my problem is I'm a thinker, I think.

07:19.464 --> 07:23.791
And you know, rational people, thoughtful people, thinking people aren't religious people.

07:23.851 --> 07:26.014
Religious people are people who have abandoned.

07:26.275 --> 07:28.398
They've jettisoned the rationality.

07:29.120 --> 07:30.642
They've given up.

07:30.978 --> 07:31.779
hard thought.

07:31.799 --> 07:36.004
They've abandoned and jettisoned their capacities for thought and reason and for consideration.

07:36.484 --> 07:40.369
And so they sort of leapt emotionally into the arms of this faith.

07:40.409 --> 07:41.991
They just take leaps of faith.

07:42.431 --> 07:52.663
So the problem, people say, is if you, for Christians and for religious people, is they don't think, but not me, I can't believe because I'm a thinker, I think.

07:54.225 --> 07:58.450
Now this text here and throughout the Bible, we're told

07:58.658 --> 08:00.861
that actually the opposite is the case.

08:02.164 --> 08:09.355
You see what it says here in verse 14, it says, as obedient children don't conform to the evil desires you had when you lived in ignorance.

08:09.375 --> 08:12.560
Life without God is a thoughtless life.

08:13.662 --> 08:14.663
Now let me show you what I mean.

08:15.945 --> 08:21.554
Some of you, having come to redeemer for a while, have heard arguments up here.

08:22.338 --> 08:25.203
rational arguments for why do we believe what we believe?

08:25.283 --> 08:26.905
How do we know Christianity is true?

08:27.306 --> 08:29.910
And they sound so wonderfully compelling.

08:29.990 --> 08:32.134
So you go out and you try them on people.

08:33.897 --> 08:35.860
And for some reason, they don't like them.

08:38.084 --> 08:38.644
You know why?

08:38.664 --> 08:40.267
Here's how they go.

08:40.347 --> 08:46.778
For example, ask somebody sometime who says, well, you know, you're a religious fine, but I'm not a religious person.

08:46.798 --> 08:47.258
I'm a thinker.

08:47.338 --> 08:48.500
OK, OK, so you say think.

08:48.901 --> 08:49.522
Think with me.

08:50.498 --> 08:51.340
What are you living for?

08:51.400 --> 08:52.943
What's the meaning of your life anyway?

08:52.963 --> 09:01.201
If somebody came up to you after the service and said, I'd like you to spend your entire afternoon with me tomorrow, what would you say?

09:01.241 --> 09:05.530
You would probably say, what for?

09:06.131 --> 09:07.113
What's the purpose?

09:07.133 --> 09:09.458
Articulate for me the purpose of our meeting.

09:09.570 --> 09:13.195
He said, well, I'm not really sure the person says, but I would like to meet with you.

09:13.215 --> 09:15.239
And you'll probably say, like a busy New Yorker.

09:15.259 --> 09:22.289
He said, well, a whole afternoon, unless you can articulate the purpose, unless you can tell me what it's about, it'll be a waste of time.

09:23.110 --> 09:25.113
Well, that's only logical.

09:25.153 --> 09:26.455
All right, let me ask you a question.

09:27.116 --> 09:28.038
What is your life about?

09:29.660 --> 09:30.542
What is your life for?

09:30.582 --> 09:32.204
Well, you know what I say?

09:32.224 --> 09:32.645
I'm working.

09:32.665 --> 09:33.466
I have a career.

09:33.847 --> 09:34.748
OK, great.

09:34.768 --> 09:35.229
You have a career.

09:35.669 --> 09:36.370
What is it for?

09:37.332 --> 09:38.834
What do you actually hope to accomplish?

09:39.874 --> 09:41.036
What is the meaning of your life?

09:41.517 --> 09:43.701
What difference will it make that you've lived?

09:45.103 --> 09:46.445
And people don't like to be asked that.

09:46.485 --> 09:48.749
Oh, no, they really don't like it at all.

09:48.849 --> 09:50.552
And yet I have to press you a little bit on this.

09:51.253 --> 09:54.719
You would not spend an afternoon with me unless you knew the reason for it.

09:54.739 --> 09:56.041
Otherwise it would be a waste.

09:56.062 --> 09:58.125
And yet you can't tell me the reason for your life.

09:58.726 --> 10:00.249
You can't tell me what your life's about.

10:00.289 --> 10:02.192
And how do you know it's not a waste?

10:03.013 --> 10:03.614
What's it for?

10:03.815 --> 10:05.778
What's the purpose of your life?

10:06.882 --> 10:08.023
See, what is its meaning?

10:08.364 --> 10:09.585
People don't want to think about that.

10:09.605 --> 10:11.367
They'll get irritated with you at a certain point.

10:11.948 --> 10:14.972
Very quickly, they'll start to get irritated with you.

10:15.012 --> 10:15.272
Why?

10:15.292 --> 10:16.594
They don't want to think.

10:17.174 --> 10:18.516
They don't want to think about these things.

10:18.936 --> 10:23.362
The average person's lifestyle and behavior is based on no thought.

10:25.905 --> 10:27.507
No thinking out of philosophy of life.

10:27.527 --> 10:28.348
They don't want to think about that.

10:28.368 --> 10:29.609
They think it's morbid to think about that.

10:29.629 --> 10:31.191
They say, oh, you're getting religious on me.

10:32.252 --> 10:33.714
What do you mean getting religious on you?

10:34.018 --> 10:36.501
You wouldn't meet with me all afternoon because you wanted a purpose.

10:36.521 --> 10:38.724
I'm asking you, what is your purpose?

10:38.744 --> 10:49.037
If there's no God, if you don't know if there is a God, if when you die, you're rot, then isn't it possible that nothing you are doing has any meaning and nothing you are doing makes any difference?

10:49.057 --> 10:59.451
And when we die, we rot and eventually the universe is going to burn up, but nothing that you do, whether you're a violent person or a compassionate person will make any difference, have you thought that through?

10:59.491 --> 11:02.194
They don't want to think it through.

11:03.170 --> 11:04.432
Well, let me give you another example.

11:05.393 --> 11:10.599
This week we went to see a movie that's not a particularly good movie, but it's a couple of good scenes in it.

11:10.679 --> 11:12.902
It's the movie Fearless with Jeff Bridges in it.

11:13.863 --> 11:17.207
And at one point Jeff Bridges, he's a survivor of a plane crash.

11:17.327 --> 11:20.892
And he's talking with a young woman who's also a survivor of a plane crash.

11:22.213 --> 11:25.778
And he says to you, she believes in God, and he doesn't.

11:25.818 --> 11:28.161
He says, you know, people don't really believe in God.

11:29.222 --> 11:32.626
They just choose not to believe in nothing.

11:33.986 --> 11:37.872
He says, people want to think that life and death has a purpose to it.

11:38.453 --> 11:40.516
They like to think that they were born for a reason.

11:42.099 --> 11:45.284
Because he says, the giants needed a new home-runner, the home-run hitter.

11:45.304 --> 11:46.226
That's why I was born.

11:46.306 --> 11:49.611
Or my mother needed somebody to console her.

11:49.651 --> 11:51.975
You think that you're born for a reason.

11:51.995 --> 11:53.137
You think you die for a reason.

11:53.197 --> 11:54.819
We talk about not dying in vain.

11:55.120 --> 11:56.322
He says, it just happens.

11:56.823 --> 11:57.604
There is no God.

11:57.704 --> 11:58.806
It just happens.

11:59.787 --> 12:00.468
Life happens.

12:00.669 --> 12:01.490
Death happens.

12:02.978 --> 12:04.760
There's no reason for the life when it happens.

12:04.821 --> 12:06.703
There's no reason for the death when it happens.

12:07.404 --> 12:10.288
There's no reason for anything," he says triumphantly.

12:11.149 --> 12:15.155
And the lady looks up at him and says, well, if that's true, then there's no reason to love either.

12:15.195 --> 12:17.698
And he looks and says, what?

12:18.059 --> 12:19.921
He says, well, then there'd be no reason to love.

12:21.744 --> 12:24.688
And what is she's doing to him in her own inimical way?

12:24.748 --> 12:26.470
She stares at her because there's no answer.

12:26.790 --> 12:29.394
She's doing what we call presuppositional apologetics.

12:31.842 --> 12:34.886
Which means what she's pulling out, she's pulling the rug out.

12:34.906 --> 12:38.451
She says, you know, if that's true, why are you here trying to help me?

12:39.172 --> 12:41.375
The whole idea was he was a plane crash survivor.

12:41.415 --> 12:42.477
She was a plane crash survivor.

12:42.517 --> 12:44.500
They were having troubles adjusting, so he was there to help.

12:45.501 --> 12:48.005
Yes, he says, you know, the one thing you have to do is you have to get rid of your idea.

12:48.025 --> 12:51.349
The only way to help yourself is to get rid of your idea of God.

12:51.650 --> 12:52.191
Get rid of it.

12:53.252 --> 12:55.375
You see, that's the reason why you're all full of guilt and shame.

12:55.475 --> 12:55.996
Get rid of it.

12:56.497 --> 12:57.258
I'm here to help you.

12:57.759 --> 13:00.242
She says, well, if there is no God,

13:00.610 --> 13:01.652
Why should you help me?

13:01.852 --> 13:03.295
Why should you just scratch my eyes out?

13:03.876 --> 13:05.580
You see, put it this way.

13:06.081 --> 13:10.149
Ask somebody in typical person in Manhattan will say racism is wrong.

13:11.993 --> 13:13.816
You know, intolerance is wrong.

13:14.177 --> 13:15.940
But sexually, you can do pretty much what you want.

13:16.381 --> 13:17.744
Now, just ask for a question.

13:17.784 --> 13:18.946
Ask this question.

13:19.026 --> 13:22.834
What is the basis for that distinction

13:23.714 --> 13:26.118
Well, you say, everybody knows that racism is wrong.

13:26.138 --> 13:32.307
The person says, oh, well, there have been countries where everybody knew that certain races should go into the gas chamber.

13:32.407 --> 13:38.056
I don't think we should determine morality by a popular voter.

13:38.076 --> 13:41.741
Are you saying that as long as the majority of people think something is right, therefore it's right?

13:41.842 --> 13:42.142
Oh, no.

13:42.923 --> 13:46.789
Actually, the person says, I believe that everybody has to make up their mind on their own.

13:46.829 --> 13:48.291
There is no moral absolutes.

13:48.372 --> 13:50.675
We have to all determine for ourselves what is right and wrong.

13:51.276 --> 13:52.658
While you ask yourself, you mean,

13:53.410 --> 13:54.952
There's nothing that's always wrong.

13:55.513 --> 13:56.635
Isn't torture always wrong?

13:56.735 --> 13:58.057
Oh, of course, torture is always wrong.

13:58.117 --> 13:58.397
Why?

14:00.641 --> 14:02.263
Maybe that's just what some people like to do.

14:03.385 --> 14:04.386
Maybe that's right for them.

14:04.426 --> 14:09.714
Oh, no, torture is always wrong because you can't mess up with, you can't mess with human beings.

14:09.794 --> 14:10.195
Why not?

14:10.976 --> 14:15.943
On what basis have you determined that people are really more valuable than rocks?

14:16.284 --> 14:17.005
On what basis?

14:19.128 --> 14:20.370
And the person you see,

14:20.610 --> 14:21.391
they'll get mad at you.

14:21.592 --> 14:22.193
They always do.

14:22.213 --> 14:24.657
If you're trying this out on people, you know why?

14:24.697 --> 14:25.879
They don't want to think.

14:27.802 --> 14:35.214
Listen, most of the simplest uneducated Christians have worked out epistemology issues.

14:35.695 --> 14:36.536
They don't know the name.

14:36.836 --> 14:38.119
They've worked out metaphysical issues.

14:38.139 --> 14:39.942
They've worked out ethical issues.

14:40.202 --> 14:41.244
Let me ask you a question.

14:41.384 --> 14:43.988
This is a typical Christian's framework.

14:44.008 --> 14:45.170
A Christian would say,

14:46.178 --> 14:56.152
I discovered that there was a body of evidence that indicated that there was a man that lived 2,000 years ago who claimed to be God and convinced a lot of monotheistic people that he was God and that he'd been raised from the dead.

14:56.573 --> 15:04.223
And I discovered there was a 500 people that saw eyewitness account that claimed they saw this man raised from the dead and was documented.

15:04.744 --> 15:07.468
And I began to study the evidence.

15:07.488 --> 15:08.710
This is how a Christian would speak.

15:09.010 --> 15:14.578
I began to study the evidence and as hard as it is to believe that this man was God, I decided

15:15.202 --> 15:20.370
that the alternative explanations for the phenomenon of this man were even more incredible.

15:20.731 --> 15:23.075
And I decided to believe that he was who he said he was.

15:24.096 --> 15:26.280
On the basis of the evidence, on the basis of weighing it up.

15:26.781 --> 15:29.325
Now if he is God, therefore he's my author.

15:29.365 --> 15:33.111
And that means that I have a purpose in life.

15:33.211 --> 15:34.633
I know why I was built.

15:34.653 --> 15:35.394
I was built for him.

15:35.695 --> 15:37.718
And I know what's right and wrong, whatever his will is.

15:38.139 --> 15:39.260
Is he perfectly coherent?

15:39.881 --> 15:40.242
All right.

15:40.482 --> 15:45.208
based on evidence, based on rationality, perfectly coherent, and then go further.

15:45.229 --> 15:52.198
The Christian says, and you know, as I've begun to live this life in faith, I have found that it fits my nature.

15:53.159 --> 16:02.592
I've found through personal experiences, I began to give myself to the will of this one that I've decided to believe in, I began to find that he fits me.

16:03.954 --> 16:09.682
The things that he says, the things that he's done, they fit my nature.

16:10.146 --> 16:16.393
that one writer said, I'd been all my life a bell, and I never knew it till he picked me up and wrung me.

16:17.755 --> 16:25.904
And I found out not only is this fitting me in a way I never thought before, but I find out that there are millions of people over a couple thousand years who have found the same thing out.

16:26.345 --> 16:34.975
And I read the works of Christians who lived a thousand years ago, and I read their experience with Jesus, and I discover this is the same relationship I've got with Jesus.

16:36.456 --> 16:37.938
Does that sound like a leap of faith?

16:38.850 --> 16:40.051
Sure, there's faith in there.

16:40.191 --> 16:42.114
Does that sound like you're not thinking?

16:42.654 --> 16:43.255
Not at all.

16:43.855 --> 16:45.217
Let me show you a leap of faith.

16:45.257 --> 16:50.343
Somebody who's, you press them and you say, well, listen, how do you know torture is wrong if there is no God?

16:50.843 --> 16:53.546
How do you know people are more valuable than rocks if there is no God?

16:53.566 --> 16:54.667
How do you know there's any meaning in life?

16:54.707 --> 16:58.491
And they say, we just know, we just know that people are valuable just because I know it.

16:59.613 --> 17:00.654
Oh, that's a leap of faith.

17:03.056 --> 17:04.198
That's thoughtlessness.

17:05.439 --> 17:06.180
That's ignorance.

17:06.861 --> 17:08.242
That's a bifurcation.

17:08.802 --> 17:11.405
between your life and your thinking.

17:12.447 --> 17:15.270
Friends, life without God is a thoughtless life.

17:16.812 --> 17:19.896
A holy life means you integrate how you live.

17:20.136 --> 17:26.184
You know why you're doing the things you're doing because you're always thinking, what is the meaning of my life and you have it in front of you?

17:27.466 --> 17:35.716
And you always look at, and that comes to my second point now, but you're always looking at what is right and wrong on the basis of the meaning of life, on the basis of who you know God is and who you know you are.

17:35.977 --> 17:36.978
There's an integration.

17:39.586 --> 17:40.968
Don't live a life of ignorance.

17:41.068 --> 17:42.249
Don't go back to that life.

17:43.711 --> 17:43.811
Okay?

17:44.111 --> 17:47.996
So holy life is a coherent life of integration of thought and life.

17:48.316 --> 17:52.821
Secondly, just as we said, a life without God is a thoughtless life.

17:53.382 --> 17:56.305
Secondly, a life without God is an imitative life.

17:56.465 --> 18:07.858
Look, down to verse 18, for you know that it was not with perishable things such as silver or gold that you were redeemed from the empty way of life handed down to you from your forefathers.

18:08.866 --> 18:18.517
So my second contrast is life without God is an imitative life, but life, a holy life, is an examined life.

18:20.119 --> 18:22.422
See, let me put it this way.

18:23.222 --> 18:32.773
Again, just like I said, a lot of people in Manhattan, a lot of people in New York I meet say, I'm not a religious person because I think so much.

18:33.334 --> 18:36.818
And I'm trying to show that ordinarily,

18:37.026 --> 18:40.271
A life without God is not a thinking life or reflective life.

18:40.311 --> 18:41.152
It's a thoughtless life.

18:42.214 --> 18:47.843
But secondly, a lot of people say, well, I'm not a religious person because I'm not a conformist.

18:47.903 --> 18:49.445
I'm an original, I think for myself.

18:49.505 --> 18:50.667
That's not what Peter says.

18:51.088 --> 18:51.829
And I think he's right.

18:53.171 --> 18:58.940
He says, you know, a lot of people, especially people come to Manhattan and they say, ah, I got out of bourgeois middle America.

18:58.960 --> 18:59.901
I live in Manhattan now.

18:59.921 --> 19:01.263
I'm a sophisticated person.

19:02.465 --> 19:05.810
I think for myself, well, you know, what do you mean you think for yourself?

19:06.338 --> 19:12.467
You see, if you're a Christian in Manhattan, you've really got to think for yourself.

19:12.487 --> 19:16.512
You open up the New York Times, you read the op-ed pages, and you're getting, what's happening?

19:16.853 --> 19:21.119
Your faith, your beliefs, your worldview is getting blasted with every article.

19:21.660 --> 19:22.701
You got to think for yourself.

19:23.542 --> 19:27.207
You know, most people in Manhattan open up their newspapers of their choice, and they're just kind of affirmed.

19:27.247 --> 19:31.433
And you get into your particular imitative style of unbelief.

19:31.493 --> 19:34.738
Peter says, unbelief is handed down

19:35.330 --> 19:38.274
We see people doing certain things, and so we do them.

19:38.294 --> 19:38.974
You know, in C.S.

19:39.034 --> 19:49.727
Lewis's book, The Great Divorce, is a great place where a man who had lost his faith, you know, he'd used to believe, but he'd lost his faith because he went to college and he began to think.

19:50.288 --> 19:53.552
And you know, his friend said to him, is that really what happened?

19:54.653 --> 19:56.215
Don't you remember how we really lost our faith?

19:57.177 --> 19:58.418
We didn't want to be laughed at.

19:59.970 --> 20:05.097
We heard a lot of other people saying things, and we wanted them to think that we were smart and intelligent and sophisticated too.

20:05.637 --> 20:17.653
We wrote the kinds of papers that our professors thought were courageous and relevant and creative, and he said, we never thought our way out of the faith.

20:18.334 --> 20:18.615
You see?

20:19.255 --> 20:24.242
We just wanted to imitate what was around us, and that's exactly what Peter's talking about.

20:24.322 --> 20:25.664
You know, we've all got our uniforms.

20:25.684 --> 20:31.973
There's certain kinds of, you know, if you say, I'm a sophisticated person, I've thrown off bourgeois, you know, middle America values.

20:31.993 --> 20:33.435
Well, you have in Manhattan.

20:33.455 --> 20:35.998
The only way you let people know that is you have to dress in a certain way.

20:37.260 --> 20:40.545
You know, you have to, you have to dress downtown or you may be addressed uptown.

20:40.565 --> 20:42.648
But the point is there's uniforms here.

20:43.910 --> 20:45.352
There is imitation going on here.

20:46.593 --> 20:49.397
What it means to be a holy person, however, is utterly different.

20:50.379 --> 20:51.881
Nothing has passed down to us.

20:52.341 --> 20:52.722
Look.

20:53.890 --> 20:59.476
The Bible says that to be a holy person means now Jesus is your authority and the Word of God is your authority.

20:59.836 --> 21:02.820
And it doesn't matter if you say, I'm Italian, I've always done things in Italian way.

21:03.120 --> 21:03.761
Is it biblical?

21:05.903 --> 21:06.704
I'm Park Avenue.

21:06.784 --> 21:07.465
Is it biblical?

21:07.785 --> 21:08.866
We've always done things this way.

21:09.026 --> 21:09.687
Is it biblical?

21:11.129 --> 21:15.493
Is it in conformity with your master and his will and your new self?

21:16.174 --> 21:17.836
Well, we've always done things because I'm a southerner.

21:17.956 --> 21:19.858
Is it Christian?

21:20.194 --> 21:22.597
We've always done things this way because I'm from Brooklyn.

21:22.617 --> 21:23.338
Is it Christian?

21:23.899 --> 21:24.380
I'm Irish.

21:24.400 --> 21:25.080
Is it Christian?

21:26.002 --> 21:31.789
You see, the great thing about being a Christian is you're pulled up out of anything that was passed down to you.

21:33.011 --> 21:34.593
You don't say, well, this is the way I am.

21:34.633 --> 21:35.694
This is the way my parents were.

21:35.714 --> 21:36.756
This is the way my family was.

21:37.036 --> 21:38.358
This is the way my peers are.

21:38.578 --> 21:46.509
This is the way the people are who read the books that I read and read the journals that we read and hang out in the same parties that we hang out.

21:46.529 --> 21:47.570
This is the way we are.

21:47.778 --> 21:50.281
A Christian's life is utterly examined.

21:50.461 --> 21:51.883
Every bit of it is examined.

21:51.983 --> 21:54.206
Every single part of it's examined.

21:56.329 --> 21:59.213
Why is there so much pain and suffering in the world?

21:59.693 --> 22:02.016
And how do we handle it in a way that won't destroy us?

22:02.317 --> 22:05.641
But could actually make us stronger, wiser, and more hopeful?

22:06.342 --> 22:15.954
All month long on Gospel and Life, Tim Keller is teaching from the book of 1 Peter, and looking at how Peter encouraged early believers who were facing intense suffering in pain.

22:16.386 --> 22:19.090
in his book Walking with God Through Pain and Suffering.

22:19.138 --> 22:27.005
Dr. Keller takes a deeper look at how, with God's help, we can face life's most intense challenges and confront the hard questions on suffering.

22:27.545 --> 22:33.791
Through deep pastoral insight and real life stories, Dr. Keller explores how we can face pain and suffering in our own lives.

22:34.331 --> 22:43.839
This month, walking with God through pain and suffering is our thank you for your gift to help Gospel and Life share the message of Christ's love and compassion with people all over the world.

22:44.340 --> 22:49.124
So request your copy today at gospelandlife.com.

22:49.104 --> 22:53.910
Now, here's Dr. Keller with the remainder of today's teaching.

22:57.053 --> 23:08.727
You know, one of my favorite memories of a good example of this was how when I went, you know, as a Yankee, as a Northeastern college educated kid, I took a church in a blue collar southern town.

23:09.769 --> 23:11.671
And you see, there's a culture there.

23:11.731 --> 23:14.554
And I remember there was several marks of that culture.

23:14.594 --> 23:17.778
That culture was much more frugal than I was used to.

23:18.754 --> 23:21.959
That culture was much more hospitable and less privatized than I was used to.

23:21.999 --> 23:27.787
That culture was much more negative and scornful of education than I was used to.

23:27.827 --> 23:32.574
And that culture was much more full of racial stereotypes than I was used to.

23:32.614 --> 23:38.262
And as a result, I could see all these differences, but very often the people who were living in the culture couldn't.

23:38.302 --> 23:43.770
And I remember one man, a friend of mine who did not even graduate from junior high school.

23:44.431 --> 23:46.834
When he became a Christian, he could hardly read

23:48.098 --> 23:52.103
And yet I remember when he became a Christian, he grasped what it meant to be holy.

23:52.764 --> 23:57.389
He knew just because all the other good old boys did things, didn't mean that that's the way he should live.

23:59.072 --> 24:07.822
And so he began to examine, actually he taught himself virtually to read in order to live a holy life, so he could study the Bible, so he could think things out.

24:08.383 --> 24:10.686
He awoke, and here's what happened.

24:11.106 --> 24:17.234
He began to realize that the fact that he was more frugal than I was, but that's a biblical value I had to learn.

24:18.498 --> 24:21.342
And the fact that he was more hospitable than I was, that was a biblical value.

24:21.742 --> 24:27.330
But his scorn of education, he realized was a kind of ego defense mechanism, and his racial stereotype was also sinful.

24:29.453 --> 24:30.134
What was he doing?

24:31.816 --> 24:34.239
He refused to take what was handed down to him.

24:35.681 --> 24:37.204
A holy life is an examined life.

24:37.364 --> 24:38.045
Isn't this interesting?

24:38.305 --> 24:41.790
You know, life without God's supposed to be sophisticated, but actually it's thoughtless.

24:42.511 --> 24:47.858
Life without God is supposed to be original, you know, and creative, and actually

24:48.098 --> 24:48.919
It's imitative.

24:49.800 --> 24:59.454
Thirdly, life without God is a life of slavery without authority.

25:00.976 --> 25:04.782
And the holy life is a life of freedom under authority.

25:04.922 --> 25:06.524
Now that sounds weird.

25:06.605 --> 25:08.407
If you're under authority, you're not supposed to be free, right?

25:08.708 --> 25:10.110
No, look, look carefully.

25:10.851 --> 25:13.114
First Peter, look at this verse.

25:13.995 --> 25:16.018
As obedient children,

25:16.322 --> 25:19.505
Don't conform to the evil desires you had.

25:19.525 --> 25:28.013
Now, unfortunately, this is another one of those places where the text translation is not only wimpy, but kind of misleading.

25:28.794 --> 25:33.718
The word conform is the word that means to be shaped or molded.

25:34.739 --> 25:42.567
And the word evil desires, the translation of the word evil desires, those two words is the translation of one word, epithemaia, which is really a poor translation.

25:42.607 --> 25:43.187
Here's why.

25:44.228 --> 25:46.290
The word epithemaia means

25:46.402 --> 25:48.344
an inordinate desire.

25:51.348 --> 25:55.332
Think of Abraham Maslow's, remember hierarchy of needs, the pyramid.

25:55.893 --> 25:58.055
And he said, you want more basic needs, you need to eat and drink.

25:58.776 --> 26:01.579
And then you move up, you need relaxation and recreation.

26:02.000 --> 26:03.542
And another need is sexuality.

26:04.022 --> 26:08.187
Then you keep moving up, you know, it's a more complex needs.

26:08.427 --> 26:10.770
You need to be loved.

26:11.458 --> 26:13.921
You need to feel like you accomplish things, you see.

26:14.522 --> 26:19.188
You need to see your significance in the world, and these are all needs.

26:19.549 --> 26:22.293
Now, every one of those things is a legitimate need.

26:22.313 --> 26:23.434
They're all created by God.

26:24.616 --> 26:25.837
God invented food and drink.

26:25.898 --> 26:26.498
He likes them.

26:27.680 --> 26:29.002
God invented rest.

26:29.242 --> 26:30.764
You know, the seventh day he rested.

26:30.804 --> 26:32.787
That's what it says in Genesis.

26:33.228 --> 26:35.731
God invented sex, and he thought it was good.

26:37.173 --> 26:40.978
God invented our social needs for approval of other people.

26:41.570 --> 26:44.575
God gave us the desire to work and to accomplish something.

26:44.595 --> 26:45.175
They're all good.

26:45.236 --> 26:51.525
But Peter says that a godless life is not a life so much of evil desires.

26:51.565 --> 26:53.328
That's a bad translation of this word.

26:53.949 --> 27:02.441
It gives you the impression what's talking about are people who pillage and murder and do violence and so forth.

27:02.461 --> 27:03.603
That's not what we're talking about.

27:04.885 --> 27:06.568
He says, you used to be molded.

27:06.628 --> 27:07.930
You used to be fashion.

27:07.970 --> 27:10.834
You used to be utterly controlled by good desires.

27:12.386 --> 27:13.848
that had become an ordinate.

27:14.328 --> 27:15.109
That's what the word means.

27:15.349 --> 27:17.972
Out of order, too important to you.

27:18.713 --> 27:19.574
Good things.

27:21.456 --> 27:32.348
Thomas Oden, we talked about this last week, but Tom Oden, who teaches at the graduate school at Drew, has a fascinating book in which he lays out a couple of principles.

27:33.490 --> 27:36.433
He says, everybody has to live for something.

27:36.493 --> 27:40.978
Remember I told you before, people don't want to think about what they're living for, but everybody has to live for something.

27:41.122 --> 27:46.950
Everybody has to have some central value that is the basis on which we make decisions.

27:47.110 --> 27:56.103
I mean, the only way you can make priority decisions, the only way you can decide this and not this, is if you have a hierarchy of values and there's something that is your ultimate value, your ultimate reason for living.

27:56.143 --> 28:03.873
It could be attractiveness, it could be approval of people, it could be power, it could be anything, but everybody's got to have something that you live for.

28:03.933 --> 28:10.322
Thomas Oden said, that central value is that without which you cannot receive life joyfully.

28:11.490 --> 28:13.913
So if you don't have that, your life falls apart.

28:15.656 --> 28:24.968
He says, now, you can either make God your central value, which is an infinite center, or you can put something finite in the way, something finite in the center.

28:25.429 --> 28:38.226
And when that happens, he says, to the degree that I center my life on a finite value instead of God, to that degree I relate to my past with guilt and to my future with anxiety.

28:38.498 --> 28:41.424
And this is what he says, and there's a couple of quotes from him.

28:42.106 --> 28:51.145
He says, look, he says, for example, my relationship to the future will be one of anxiety to the degree that I have idolized finite values.

28:51.866 --> 28:52.528
And this is a quote.

28:52.928 --> 28:59.442
Anxiety becomes neurotically intensified to the degree that I have idolized finite values that properly should have been regarded as limited.

28:59.938 --> 29:09.530
And he says, if the thing I'm living for is money, or the thing I'm living for is my children, or the thing I'm living for is the Republican Party or the Democratic Party, I'm always going to be experiencing anxiety.

29:10.030 --> 29:12.954
Because those finite values cannot last.

29:13.775 --> 29:15.817
And so I will always feel threatened.

29:17.580 --> 29:23.046
On the other hand, he says, my relationship to the past will be one of guilt.

29:23.066 --> 29:28.853
Guilt becomes neurotically intensified to the degree that I have idolized finite values that properly I should have regarded as limited.

29:28.933 --> 29:29.394
Why?

29:30.946 --> 29:40.235
Because if you've decided the only way which I know I'm going to be able to look myself in the mirror is because of this value.

29:40.815 --> 29:41.556
I will achieve.

29:42.016 --> 29:42.857
I will be loved.

29:43.158 --> 29:43.858
I will look good.

29:43.938 --> 29:55.830
Whatever you decide you've got to have in order to feel that you have meaning in life, when you fail those standards, finite gods never forgive ever.

29:57.591 --> 29:58.692
You're always down on yourself.

29:59.233 --> 30:00.594
What is Thomas Ode and saying?

30:01.090 --> 30:06.576
I have guilt in my life to the degree that I idolize finite values.

30:06.716 --> 30:10.120
I have anxiety in my life to the degree that I idolize finite values.

30:10.340 --> 30:11.661
And that's what Peter's talking about.

30:13.624 --> 30:21.372
What he is saying is life without God necessarily means I am driven by inordinate desires.

30:22.794 --> 30:27.779
Good desires for good things that now fill me with anxiety and fill me with guilt.

30:29.761 --> 30:30.642
Isn't it interesting?

30:30.978 --> 30:34.523
A life without God is supposed to be sophisticated, but it's thoughtless.

30:34.643 --> 30:37.968
A life without God is supposed to be original, but it's imitative.

30:38.068 --> 30:41.252
A life without God is supposed to be free, but it's a life of bondage.

30:43.776 --> 30:49.183
However, the holy life, and this, of course, is the last thing we're looking at here, a holy life is different.

30:49.203 --> 30:49.624
It's a thought.

30:49.764 --> 30:52.487
It's a life of coherence between thought and life.

30:52.528 --> 30:53.769
It's a life of examination.

30:54.230 --> 30:57.815
And lastly, it's a life of freedom under authority.

30:58.035 --> 31:00.178
Look, as obedient

31:00.546 --> 31:01.267
children.

31:02.148 --> 31:04.993
Let's just look at that, and this is the final point.

31:05.093 --> 31:06.355
You know what it means to be a holy person?

31:06.515 --> 31:08.418
First of all, it means you're obedient.

31:10.121 --> 31:12.124
It means you're obedient, verse 14.

31:12.144 --> 31:19.735
And unfortunately, the word obedience means, yes, to be holy, you have to submit your will to another's.

31:22.199 --> 31:26.866
To be obedient means, there's a submission of your will to the will of someone else.

31:26.978 --> 31:29.320
There's really two basic epistemologies.

31:29.340 --> 31:33.865
There's two basic ways of knowing that are dominant in New York right now.

31:34.786 --> 31:36.407
And these are kind of fanciful names.

31:36.808 --> 31:41.673
There's the scientific view of life and the new agistic view of life.

31:42.674 --> 31:45.877
And the scientific view of life says, you know, there is no supernatural.

31:46.477 --> 31:47.879
There is no spiritual realm.

31:47.919 --> 31:50.541
You know, all that exists is matter.

31:51.823 --> 31:53.244
And when you die, you rot.

31:54.365 --> 31:55.186
And that's that.

31:56.226 --> 31:56.967
That's one view.

31:57.628 --> 31:59.911
So you live your life the way you decide.

32:00.391 --> 32:01.553
However, you see you fit.

32:02.434 --> 32:03.836
Then there's the new agistic view.

32:03.856 --> 32:06.059
And of course, the new agistic view is growing.

32:06.740 --> 32:09.523
And new agism isn't just one particular group.

32:09.563 --> 32:14.270
But new agism, a new agistic view says, ah, that's not true.

32:14.310 --> 32:16.432
The scientific view is wrong.

32:17.193 --> 32:18.275
Everything is divine.

32:18.335 --> 32:19.336
Everything is sacred.

32:19.396 --> 32:20.658
God is in everything.

32:21.058 --> 32:22.359
God is throughout everything.

32:22.620 --> 32:26.103
You are God yourself, and you must come into contact with it.

32:26.504 --> 32:30.448
You must get in touch with the greatness of what you are and the greatness of who you are.

32:33.111 --> 32:38.917
But what's so funny is those two views look like they're against each other, but they agree in one area.

32:39.418 --> 32:41.520
Neither of them has any concept of obedience.

32:43.082 --> 32:45.865
The scientific view says there's no obedience, there's no one to obey.

32:45.925 --> 32:47.186
Do what you want.

32:47.650 --> 32:52.796
The New Ageistic view, though, says, get in touch with God, but you see, this is a God that's impersonal, not a God that speaks.

32:54.218 --> 33:00.966
If you want to understand how New Ageism believes that you should get in touch with God, you just watch Luke Skywalker, you know?

33:01.326 --> 33:03.429
What does Obi-Wan Kenobi say to Luke Skywalker?

33:03.809 --> 33:05.231
Reach out with your feelings.

33:06.152 --> 33:07.514
Get in touch with your feelings.

33:08.675 --> 33:10.137
Okay, no obedience.

33:10.958 --> 33:12.079
No obedience at all.

33:13.962 --> 33:17.586
A holy life is an obedient life.

33:17.954 --> 33:26.122
Right here, Christianity is running a head-on collision with the two dominant worldviews of New York City.

33:27.123 --> 33:28.124
What does it mean to be holy?

33:28.264 --> 33:30.566
It means to say, use me.

33:31.306 --> 33:32.408
It means to be cut out.

33:33.348 --> 33:35.210
It means to say, I belong to you.

33:35.751 --> 33:41.476
It means to say, you have your will, oh Lord, and where my will crosses your will, my will goes.

33:43.678 --> 33:44.799
Otherwise, you're not really his.

33:44.979 --> 33:46.621
In fact, let's go one step further.

33:46.921 --> 33:47.922
You notice down here,

33:48.482 --> 33:54.009
In verse 15, it says, as ye who called you as holy, so be holy in all you do.

33:54.029 --> 33:55.230
Let me push this a little further.

33:57.153 --> 33:59.876
What it means to be holy means to be wholly obedient.

34:00.637 --> 34:07.746
If there's any area of your life in which you're not being obedient, you're actually not being obedient at all.

34:08.087 --> 34:17.138
See, some people will say to me, well, I'm a Christian and I am obeying God, except there.

34:18.434 --> 34:19.335
And I'll get it together.

34:19.376 --> 34:20.758
All right.

34:21.800 --> 34:23.442
You're not obeying God except there.

34:23.623 --> 34:25.606
There's no such thing as obeying God except there.

34:27.168 --> 34:27.849
Think of it this way.

34:28.430 --> 34:33.699
If you can say to somebody, you can have the whole house except for that room.

34:34.560 --> 34:36.624
You can have the whole house, but you can never go in that room.

34:37.886 --> 34:42.634
Well, if you're in a position to tell somebody that they have the whole house except for that room, they don't have the house.

34:44.256 --> 34:45.298
You have the house.

34:46.946 --> 34:55.836
even if you only live in that room and you give all the rest of the house to that person, if you can keep that person out of that room, you still own the house.

34:57.718 --> 35:06.908
And if you say, well, you know, I'm going to submit to what Jesus says about this area of my life and this area of my life, but not this area, not now, right now.

35:07.268 --> 35:07.969
No, I'm not right now.

35:08.249 --> 35:09.671
But I'll give him my life in every other way.

35:09.691 --> 35:10.592
You haven't done it at all.

35:12.594 --> 35:12.754
You see?

35:13.122 --> 35:16.066
But just as he who called you is holy, be holy in all you do.

35:16.367 --> 35:17.528
Anything else isn't holy.

35:17.548 --> 35:21.173
I'm not saying to be holy you have to be perfectly obedient, nobody is.

35:21.794 --> 35:22.916
We've been through this before.

35:24.638 --> 35:32.309
A person is a Christian strictly because Jesus died for them, they rest and trust in that, and therefore they're forgiven.

35:33.671 --> 35:38.738
But the only proper response and the only way you can know that you receive Christ as Savior

35:39.106 --> 35:48.781
And the only way, the only proper response to him giving himself utterly for you on the cross is you giving yourself utterly to him right now.

35:49.823 --> 35:51.345
Anything else is inappropriate.

35:52.407 --> 35:54.230
Anything else is not holy.

35:54.270 --> 35:56.573
To be holy doesn't mean to be perfectly obedient.

35:56.593 --> 36:02.462
To be holy means to be completely submitted in the sense of saying, I take my hands off my life.

36:03.003 --> 36:06.689
I give you the rights to every room in my house.

36:06.709 --> 36:07.410
Come in.

36:07.746 --> 36:10.469
I can't keep you out of any, because the house isn't mine.

36:11.149 --> 36:19.078
But more than that, real holiness does not simply consist of external submission to authority.

36:19.398 --> 36:22.041
It says as obedient children.

36:24.523 --> 36:27.486
As obedient children, that's the last point.

36:28.948 --> 36:33.652
If you want to know what holiness means, it's not simply getting all the rules and getting all the regulations.

36:33.773 --> 36:35.154
Oh no, think about this.

36:36.002 --> 36:38.084
Why would Peter say as obedient children?

36:38.104 --> 36:40.266
Why not as obedient people or as obedient servants?

36:40.306 --> 36:41.688
Why obedient children?

36:41.728 --> 36:45.652
Because the obedience of a child is different than the obedience of a servant or a slave.

36:45.692 --> 36:50.897
A child can't obey his or her father.

36:50.917 --> 36:59.726
A child can't obey the parent unless there's already been an action on the part of the parent to receive that child.

37:00.747 --> 37:03.570
You can't obey your parent unless your parent has had you.

37:04.738 --> 37:07.241
You can't obey your parent unless your parent has adopted you.

37:07.261 --> 37:11.746
In other words, it either has to be a biological action or there has to be a legal action.

37:11.986 --> 37:17.692
But the point is that your obedience is not the reason that your parents have you.

37:20.996 --> 37:26.202
The fact that your parents have you is the reason for your obedience.

37:26.222 --> 37:27.263
That's utterly different.

37:27.483 --> 37:28.744
A slave is scared to death.

37:29.285 --> 37:31.888
A slave or a servant or an employee says, I better do well.

37:31.908 --> 37:33.970
An employee says, otherwise I could be fired.

37:34.722 --> 37:39.788
So the employee is completely motivated out of rewards and punishments.

37:39.808 --> 37:40.669
I want my reward.

37:40.950 --> 37:41.911
I fear the punishment.

37:42.211 --> 37:43.132
I want my salary.

37:43.353 --> 37:44.554
I don't want to lose my job.

37:44.814 --> 37:45.716
I want a promotion.

37:45.976 --> 37:47.097
I don't want to be demoted.

37:47.338 --> 37:48.419
See, that's the employee.

37:48.679 --> 37:51.423
And there's obedience to an employee, but no, not for a Christian.

37:51.803 --> 37:55.327
The essence here of a holy life is that you obey as children.

37:56.889 --> 37:57.811
I know I'm accepted.

37:58.652 --> 37:58.932
You see?

38:00.414 --> 38:03.858
For you know, see the entire obedience

38:03.938 --> 38:11.027
of a Christian is based on this verse, this little word for, why should you be obedient?

38:11.067 --> 38:19.697
Because you know he was not with perishable things such as silver or gold that you were redeemed, but with the precious blood of Christ, a lamb without blemish or defect.

38:20.137 --> 38:33.874
If you want to get to the very, very heart of what it means to live an obedient life as a holy person, as a child, not as an employee, to be holy God, to belong holy to him in your life,

38:34.498 --> 38:38.244
will only issue from a vision of how he wholly gave himself for you.

38:38.645 --> 38:52.688
You know, at the very end of the movie, The Bible, the one that John Histon put together some years ago, George C. Scott plays Abraham, and my wife and I can never watch that thing without weeping at the end, so we avoid it.

38:53.991 --> 38:54.431
No, we don't.

38:55.393 --> 39:00.882
But you know, here's George C. Scott, here's Abraham, and God comes to him.

39:01.250 --> 39:08.723
In Genesis 15, God said to Abraham, I will bless you and your descendants through Isaac, your son.

39:10.045 --> 39:15.575
And he walks between, God moves between the pieces of cut up animals to show.

39:15.615 --> 39:17.599
He says, I will obey my promise.

39:17.979 --> 39:20.544
I will bless you and your descendants.

39:21.005 --> 39:23.409
And if I don't, may I be cut up as these animals.

39:25.833 --> 39:26.354
And yet,

39:27.394 --> 39:32.320
Years later, God comes to Abraham and says, Abraham, you know that son that I promised I was going to bless you through?

39:32.340 --> 39:35.404
I want you to kill him.

39:36.766 --> 39:41.391
And the Bible tells us that Abraham wrestled and wrestled and wrestled.

39:41.411 --> 39:45.997
But finally, he walked up the hill with his son and he put him on the altar.

39:46.798 --> 39:51.664
And you know, in the movie, they had a little line that's not in the Bible, but it's perfectly appropriate.

39:52.305 --> 39:53.106
In the movie,

39:53.346 --> 39:55.408
as Abraham is tying up Isaac.

39:55.428 --> 39:56.970
And Isaac realizes what he's doing.

39:57.010 --> 40:01.514
He says, Father, is there nothing he cannot ask of thee?

40:03.376 --> 40:04.717
And Abraham says nothing.

40:05.558 --> 40:06.118
Why not?

40:06.879 --> 40:08.541
Why was Abraham holy?

40:08.581 --> 40:11.424
Why was Abraham holy gods at that point?

40:12.144 --> 40:16.028
Because he was just knuckling under under the naked power of God?

40:17.009 --> 40:18.651
Did Abraham just say, well, there's nothing I can do?

40:18.731 --> 40:19.752
How can I fight against God?

40:19.792 --> 40:20.132
No.

40:20.813 --> 40:22.194
The book of Hebrews tells us

40:23.394 --> 40:29.083
that he walked up with his son figuring out that somehow God was going to raise him from the dead because God would keep his promise.

40:29.864 --> 40:32.568
Ah, if Abraham was only here now, you know why?

40:32.868 --> 40:40.760
Because as soon as Abraham had holy given, even Isaac, and see everybody in this room has Isaac's, things that we want to hold on to.

40:40.800 --> 40:43.885
And yet God says, you must be holy mind, holy mind.

40:43.945 --> 40:50.435
And as Abraham was ready to give Isaac up, God says, Abraham, Abraham.

40:50.495 --> 40:52.498
And he says, here I am.

40:53.506 --> 40:54.507
Do not harm the lad.

40:54.568 --> 41:00.136
Now I know that you love me, for you did not withhold your son, your only son, whom you love from me."

41:02.179 --> 41:06.165
See, now Abraham, as an Old Testament figure, understood that God was good.

41:06.586 --> 41:07.507
That's why he obeyed.

41:08.869 --> 41:11.433
He understood that God was loving in a general way.

41:11.493 --> 41:13.876
But boy, we have something that Abraham didn't have.

41:14.337 --> 41:16.200
If Abraham was here now, you know what he would know?

41:16.741 --> 41:20.306
He would know why God was able to say, Abraham, you don't.

41:20.386 --> 41:21.327
have to kill your son.

41:21.348 --> 41:21.748
You know why?

41:22.249 --> 41:30.662
Because years after Abraham, God walked up the hill with his son, and he slew him, and there was nobody there to call out from heaven.

41:30.722 --> 41:32.645
Don't do it.

41:33.567 --> 41:36.972
And if Abraham was here now, he would look at God and say, here's why I'm holy yours.

41:37.032 --> 41:38.274
Here's why I'm holy yours.

41:39.215 --> 41:48.530
Now I know, O Lord God, that you love me, because you did not withhold your son, your only son, whom you love from me.

41:49.858 --> 41:58.391
as obedient children, for you know you are not redeemed with perishable things like silver and gold, but redeemed with the precious blood of Jesus Christ.

41:59.092 --> 42:03.058
That creates a motivation for obedience that no one else knows.

42:04.179 --> 42:05.301
It's not an oppressive thing.

42:05.441 --> 42:06.583
It's a liberating thing.

42:07.484 --> 42:11.671
We put ourselves holy under Him, holy in all that we do.

42:12.211 --> 42:14.695
Obedient in every area of life, isn't it amazing?

42:15.857 --> 42:19.282
The ungodly life is not sophisticated, it's thoughtless.

42:19.778 --> 42:21.761
It's not original.

42:21.921 --> 42:22.582
It's imitative.

42:23.043 --> 42:23.804
It's not free.

42:24.385 --> 42:25.086
This is freedom.

42:26.328 --> 42:27.730
His service is perfect freedom.

42:28.371 --> 42:31.656
You will know the truth, Jesus said, and the truth will set you free.

42:32.437 --> 42:32.918
Let's pray.

42:33.760 --> 42:48.402
Help us, O Father, to get that freedom and to get that holiness of life, which only comes from a sight of you walking up that mountain with your son and slaying him for our sins so that

42:49.442 --> 42:51.245
We could know your pardon.

42:52.087 --> 42:54.171
Thank you for taking our punishment upon yourself.

42:54.652 --> 43:09.641
And I pray, Father, that everybody in this room would know tonight that only if they give themselves holy to you, because your son gave himself holy for us, will we know the freedom and the liberty of holiness.

43:09.822 --> 43:12.146
In Jesus' name we pray, amen.

